<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2 id=3D"h.49gptdklysv5">Evaluating capabilities</=
h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">How do we measure how capable AI sys=
tems are?</span></p>
<p>For society to successfully navigate the transition to powerful AI, it=
=E2=80=99s important that there be&nbsp;an empirically-grounded expert cons=
ensus about the current and expected future impacts of AI systems. However,=
 there is currently widespread expert disagreement about the expected traje=
ctory&nbsp;of AI development, and even about the capabilities of current AI=
 systems.</p>
<p>Many AI capability benchmarks, including <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/ab=
s/2311.12022">difficult ones that target PhD-level knowledge</a>, saturate =
quickly and therefore fail to provide a continuous, extrapolatable signal o=
f AI progress. On the other hand, the real-world impact of AI systems often=
 lags behind what might be expected based on impressive benchmark scores. I=
t=E2=80=99s therefore important to create high-quality assessments of AI ca=
pabilities that actually track their real-world impact.</p>
<p>In certain national-security-critical domains=E2=80=94such as chemical, =
biological, radiological, and nuclear (CBRN) weapons development capabiliti=
es=E2=80=94these sorts of evaluations should be conducted in secured labs i=
n coordination with governments. However, there are many other capabilities=
=E2=80=94such as conducting novel research, interoperating with tools, and =
autonomously completing open-ended tasks=E2=80=94that are important for und=
erstanding AI systems=E2=80=99 impact. We would be excited to see more high=
-quality evaluations for capabilities like these, alongside human baselines=
.</p>
<p>See our past announcement <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/news/a-ne=
w-initiative-for-developing-third-party-model-evaluations">here</a>&nbsp;fo=
r more information about capabilities evaluations we are interested in more=
 work on (though note that the deadline for that initiative has passed).</p=
>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2 id=3D"h.ryzzv48oxf5o">Evaluating alignment</h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">How do we measure how aligned AI sys=
tems are?</span></p>
<p>Our measurements of frontier model alignment currently focus on relative=
ly surface-level properties, like:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Models are pleasant conversational ass=
istants</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Models refuse harmful queries<=
/li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Models avoid producing toxic text.</li=
></ul>
<p>While these properties suffice for assuring the safety of current AI cha=
tbots, we expect that future AI systems will be deployed in varied (sometim=
es high-stakes) environments under circumstances we cannot anticipate. Ther=
efore, we need better ways to measure AI systems=E2=80=99 propensities towa=
rd misaligned behavior. </p>
<p>For example, given a model, we might want to answer questions like:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Does the model have drives, goals, val=
ues, or preferences? If so, what are they?</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">For example, <a href=3D"https://www.an=
thropic.com/research/towards-understanding-sycophancy-in-language-models">w=
e=E2=80=99ve found</a>&nbsp;that our models have sycophantic tendencies: th=
ey generally prefer user-pleasing responses.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Does the model ever knowingly <a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.14093">fake being more aligned</a>&nbsp;than=
 they are? Does it ever hide its drives, goals, values, or preferences? Doe=
s it ever <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.07358v2">strategically choo=
se not to reveal</a>&nbsp;a capability it possesses?</li><li style=3D"margi=
n-left: 36pt;">Under what conditions would the model knowingly mislead a hu=
man?</li></ul>
<p>Although these questions are extremely subtle=E2=80=94and in many cases,=
 vague or ill-defined=E2=80=94they might critically bear on future deployme=
nt decisions. </p>
<p>Consider the case of a model which (1) is capable enough that it could s=
uccessfully execute on extremely harmful actions, but (2) in controlled lab=
 settings, generally avoids taking such actions. What could we do to feel c=
omfortable widely deploying such a model?</p>
<h3 id=3D"h.rew9ycn3zds2">Understanding model cognition</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">What are our models =E2=80=9Cthinkin=
g=E2=80=9D when they generate outputs?</span></p>
<p>Much AI research involves understanding AI systems in terms of their inp=
ut/output behavior. Examples of behavioral questions include: What fraction=
 of a model=E2=80=99s answers are correct? Which inputs cause a model to ge=
nerate toxic text? Do our models, when asked, claim to prioritize user inte=
rests?</p>
<p>When evaluating the extent of a model=E2=80=99s alignment, we would like=
 to not only check whether a model=E2=80=99s outputs appear benign, but als=
o understand whether the model is arriving at its outputs =E2=80=9Cfor the =
right reason.=E2=80=9D Thus, we would like to supplement understanding of m=
odel behaviors with study of the cognition underlying these behaviors. Unde=
rstanding model cognition involves asking what a model was thinking that le=
d it to exhibit some behavior of interest. For example, we might ask:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">When our model gave an answer, did it =
do so because it thought the answer was correct? Because it modeled the use=
r as believing the answer is correct? Because it thought the answer would <=
a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.13548">please the user</a>&nbsp;in oth=
er ways?</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Do our models form plans? If =
so, what are those plans?</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">What do our =
models know about their <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.04694">situat=
ions</a>? Do they have guesses about whether they are in training or how th=
ey=E2=80=99re being monitored? How does this knowledge affect their behavio=
r?</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Do our models <a href=3D"https://tr=
ansluce.org/observability-interface#example-2">know information that they d=
o not report when asked</a>?</li></ul>
<p>Understanding model cognition could be useful for <a href=3D"https://arx=
iv.org/abs/2406.04341">expediting searches</a>&nbsp;for concerning behavior=
s (e.g. during auditing or red-teaming), improving our oversight during tra=
ining, or predicting models=E2=80=99 behaviors out-of-distribution.</p>
<p>There is an extensive body of research on understanding model cognition,=
 especially in <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">mechanistic interpretabi=
lity</span>, a field centered on methods for directly decoding the internal=
 algorithms learned by trained AI systems. Rather than trying to outline th=
e contours of the mechanistic interpretability, we refer the reader to the =
<a href=3D"https://transformer-circuits.pub/">Anthropic interpretability te=
am=E2=80=99s blog</a>. </p>
<p>On the other hand, we believe there is ample space for other approaches =
to understanding model cognition. For example:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Exte=
rnalized cognition:</span>&nbsp;Inducing a model to =E2=80=9Creason out lou=
d=E2=80=9D (for example via a <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2201.11903">=
chain-of-thought</a>&nbsp;scratchpad) and studying the resulting reasoning =
trace. The core challenge here is ensuring the faithfulness of the external=
ized reasoning; see <a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/recomme=
nded-directions/#h.eph2q3u5u1yt">below</a>.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 3=
6pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Introspection</span><span style=3D"=
font-weight: 700;">:</span>&nbsp;Training models to directly verbalize the =
content of their hidden states (<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.13787=
">Binder et al., 2024</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.10949">Che=
n et al., 2024</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2401.06102">Ghandehari=
oun et al., 2024</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.05629v1">Zhuang=
 et al., 2024</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.08686">Pan et al.,=
 2024</a>). For example, could we train a model to accurately report its pl=
ans in a board game, as judged by whether the model=E2=80=99s answer accura=
tely predicts its later moves?</li></ul>
<h3 id=3D"h.a9ape49siak7">Understanding how a model's persona affects its b=
ehavior and how it generalizes out-of-distribution</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">What effects does a model=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9Cpersonality=E2=80=9D have on its behaviors?</span></p>
<p>Today's leading models generally behave in benign ways, even given unusu=
al prompts that they weren't trained on. One hypothesis for this generaliza=
tion is that they're adopting a certain persona, that of a helpful assistan=
t, which implies a set of good default behaviors. However, different assist=
ants have slightly different personas, and seemingly small changes in the p=
ersona may have important impacts on how they behave in novel situations. F=
or example, while studying <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.14093">ali=
gnment faking</a>, we found that in certain settings, only some models woul=
d fake alignment. To what extent is a model=E2=80=99s propensity to fake al=
ignment influenced by its persona or values? Is it possible that a model=E2=
=80=99s writing style and personality isn=E2=80=99t just superficial, but h=
ave wide-ranging indirect effects on a model=E2=80=99s behavior, including =
in safety-critical settings?</p>
<p>We=E2=80=99d be excited to see more work that characterizes the influenc=
es a model=E2=80=99s persona has on how it behaves across a variety of sett=
ings. For example, one could create (with few-shot prompting or training on=
 synthetic data) a suite of models with similar capabilities but different =
personas and study how these personality differences affect their behavior =
in various downstream situations.</p>
<h3 id=3D"h.eph2q3u5u1yt">Chain-of-thought faithfulness</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">When can we take a model=E2=80=99s c=
hain-of-thought at face value?</span></p>
<p>Language models don't always <a href=3D"https://proceedings.neurips.cc/p=
aper_files/paper/2023/file/ed3fea9033a80fea1376299fa7863f4a-Paper-Conferenc=
e.pdf">say what they think</a>. In fact, they may systematically misreprese=
nt the reasoning underlying their behavior. We are therefore interested in =
techniques for detecting (<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.13702">Lanh=
am et al., 2023</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.12747">Mills et =
al., 2024</a>) or ensuring (<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.11768">Ra=
dhakrishnan et al., 2023</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2401.13986">=
Chen et al., 2024</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.05518">Chua et=
 al., 2024</a>) the faithfulness of a language model's chain-of-thought (Co=
T). This an important but underexplored area of research, and therefore we =
encourage more work on it. For example, we'd be interested in answers to qu=
estions like:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">How&nbsp;does CoT faithfulness vary ac=
ross different types of tasks? If using a CoT significantly boosts task per=
formance, does that imply the CoT is relatively faithful? Does CoT faithful=
ness vary between math and social reasoning?</li><li style=3D"margin-left: =
36pt;">Can a model=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.04694">k=
nowledge about its situation</a>&nbsp;affect the faithfulness of its CoT? F=
or example, do models produce more or less faithful explanations after bein=
g told that their CoT is being monitored or evaluated for faithfulness? </l=
i><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">How can we make automatic methods for de=
tecting unfaithful CoT (<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.13702">Lanham=
 et al., 2023</a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.12747">Mills et al=
., 2024</a>, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2401.13986">Chen et al., 2024=
</a>) more efficient and higher recall?</li></ul>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2 id=3D"h.18872evr79nk">AI control</h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we ensure safety by deploying mo=
dels alongside sufficient safeguards?</span></p>
<p>Currently, the main reason we believe AI systems don=E2=80=99t pose cata=
strophic risks is that they lack many of the capabilities necessary for cau=
sing catastrophic harm (such as being able to do novel research or effectiv=
ely manipulate large numbers of people). In the future we may have AI syste=
ms that are capable enough to cause catastrophic harm, but don=E2=80=99t do=
 so because they are sufficiently aligned; if we=E2=80=99ve made sufficient=
 progress on <a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/recommended-di=
rections/#h.ryzzv48oxf5o">evaluating alignment</a>&nbsp;we can make alignme=
nt-based assurances of safety.</p>
<p>A third category of assurance we could make=E2=80=94aside from sufficien=
t alignment or lack of dangerous capabilities=E2=80=94is that we have deplo=
yed our AI systems alongside sufficient safeguards that they could not succ=
essfully cause catastrophic harm even if they tried. This strategy, known a=
s <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.06942">AI control</a>, is appropria=
te when AI systems <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">are</span>&nbsp;capa=
ble enough to cause a catastrophe if deployed with no safeguards but=E2=80=
=94when deployed in restricted environments=E2=80=94are <span style=3D"font=
-style: italic;">not</span>&nbsp;capable enough to circumvent safeguards im=
posed by a careful developer. In this section, we=E2=80=99ll&nbsp;discuss p=
ossible strategies for AI control, with a focus on run-time monitoring of A=
I systems.</p>
<h3 id=3D"h.dos4q2vcvwwj">Behavioral monitoring</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we ensure safety by having our A=
I=E2=80=99s inputs and outputs monitored by another AI?</span></p>
<p>One AI control strategy is to use an auxiliary AI system (the <span styl=
e=3D"font-style: italic;">monitor</span>) to screen the inputs and outputs =
of another untrusted AI system (the <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">act=
or</span>) (<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.10538">Naihin et al., 202=
3</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2401.13138">Chan et al., 2024</a>; =
<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.06942">Greenblatt et al., 2023</a>). =
<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.06942">Greenblatt et al. (2023)</a>&n=
bsp;study variants of this idea, including:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Trus=
ted monitoring: </span>using a less capable, but trusted, AI system to moni=
tor the actor=E2=80=99s inputs and outputs, such as using&nbsp;GPT-3.5 to s=
creen code written by a potentially malicious GPT-4.</li><li style=3D"margi=
n-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Untrusted monitoring:</spa=
n>&nbsp;using another untrusted model (for example, another instance of the=
 actor model) as a monitor.</li></ul>
<p>A core challenge for these monitoring set-ups is that monitor failures m=
ight be systematically concentrated in the same episodes where the actor be=
haves maliciously. For example, this could happen because the actor intenti=
onally subverts the monitor (e.g. by jailbreaking it) or=E2=80=94in the cas=
e of untrusted monitoring=E2=80=94because the monitor and the actor are col=
luding.</p>
<p>We are excited about work on improving the efficacy of behavioral monito=
ring. Promising directions include:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Reducing opportunities for actor-monit=
or collusion or jailbreaks, e.g. by editing or paraphrasing the actor=E2=80=
=99s output before showing it to the monitor.</li><li style=3D"margin-left:=
 36pt;">Training better monitors, e.g. by generating synthetic data that re=
alistically captures sophisticated, malicious behavior.</li><li style=3D"ma=
rgin-left: 36pt;">Better estimating failure rates for extremely rare catast=
rophic outcomes.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Developing monitoring=
 schemes that work even when the actor has access to additional affordances=
, such as memory of previous episodes or the ability to <a href=3D"https://=
arxiv.org/abs/2410.03768">pass messages</a>&nbsp;between instances.</li></u=
l>
<h3 id=3D"h.cpqnfk2ytbxk">Activation monitoring</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we ensure safety by monitoring o=
ur AI=E2=80=99s hidden states?</span></p>
<p>An alternative to monitoring an AI system=E2=80=99s input/output behavio=
r is monitoring its latent activations. For example, one could attempt to t=
rain simple probes which use a model=E2=80=99s latent activations to classi=
fy when it is writing secure vs. insecure code. This direction can be viewe=
d as a less ambitious alternative to <a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic=
.com/2025/recommended-directions/#h.rew9ycn3zds2">understanding model cogni=
tion</a>, where we search for scalable, automatic ways to detect the presen=
ce of pre-specified undesired concepts in the model=E2=80=99s internal proc=
essing.</p>
<p>This monitoring approach is promising because the model=E2=80=99s activa=
tions (1) correspond to the reasoning of the model being monitored, and (2)=
 are difficult for the model to control. For example, when using a weak mod=
el to <a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/recommended-direction=
s/#h.dos4q2vcvwwj">behaviorally monitor</a>&nbsp;a stronger code generation=
 model for insecure code, we might worry that the weak monitor would fail t=
o spot some vulnerabilities or that the code generation model would obfusca=
te its code to make vulnerabilities difficult to detect; monitoring the act=
ivations of the code generation model itself might side-step these failures=
.</p>
<p>On the other hand, there is substantial risk that activation monitors ar=
e not robust to distributional shifts. One particularly important distribut=
ion shift is the <a href=3D"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/WCj7WgFSLmyKaMw=
PR/coup-probes-catching-catastrophes-with-probes-trained-off">shift from fi=
xed datasets of synthetic data to data generated by the model itself</a>. I=
f we don=E2=80=99t have model-generated examples of the bad outputs we woul=
d like to detect, then we=E2=80=99ll need to synthetically generate outputs=
 in some other way to train activation monitors. We would then need to veri=
fy that monitors trained using these outputs generalize to actual dangerous=
 model generations of interest.</p>
<p>While there are <a href=3D"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/WCj7WgFSLmyKa=
MwPR/coup-probes-catching-catastrophes-with-probes-trained-off">signs</a>&n=
bsp;of <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.04313">life</a>&nbsp;for activ=
ation monitoring, more research is needed to make it reliable enough for de=
ployment in production AI systems.</p>
<h3 id=3D"h.qen1pon6sde">Anomaly detection</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we automatically detect when our=
 models are behaving =E2=80=9Cweirdly=E2=80=9D?</span></p>
<p>Many approaches to monitoring are supervised: they involve training a cl=
assifier on a curated dataset of positive and negative examples of bad mode=
l behaviors. However, we may not know what dangerous failures look like ahe=
ad of time. Thus, another <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">unsupervised<=
/span>&nbsp;approach to monitoring is <span style=3D"font-style: italic;"><=
a href=3D"https://www.alignment.org/blog/mechanistic-anomaly-detection-and-=
elk/">anomaly detection</a></span>: trying to detect when a model=E2=80=99s=
 computation is unusual or out of distribution in certain ways. </p>
<p>For example, suppose we have deployed a model alongside a monitor for so=
me sort of harmful behavior. We might expect our monitor to catch typical c=
ases of the harmful behavior, but to fail on rare inputs such as jailbreaks=
. We might therefore also deploy our model and monitor alongside an anomaly=
 detector which aims to flag inputs (like rare jailbreaks) which are far ou=
t-of-distribution. We could manually inspect and label such inputs, and lat=
er use them to improve the coverage of our monitor. It is plausible that ap=
plying existing anomaly detection techniques to model latent activations mi=
ght already be suitable for tasks like these; see e.g. <a href=3D"https://a=
rxiv.org/abs/2312.01037">here</a>.</p>
<p>More ambitiously, one might also try to apply anomaly detection to detec=
t when there are large differences between two models. For example, conside=
r an input where a strong model understands something that a weak model doe=
s not, leading to behavior that is novel and=E2=80=94from the perspective o=
f the weak model=E2=80=94surprising. It might be possible to automatically =
detect such inputs. This is, as far as we know, an unexplored problem setti=
ng, and we would be excited to see progress on it.</p>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2 id=3D"h.9aidfzd51piy">Scalable oversight</h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we design oversight mechanisms t=
hat will continue to work for smarter-than-human AI systems?</span></p>
<p>In traditional machine learning, one typically assumes access to a groun=
d-truth oversight signal R (such as training labels or scalar rewards) and =
trains models to perform well according to R. This works well in settings w=
here we are able to reliably discriminate good vs. bad model outputs. </p>
<p>However, it may be difficult to continue with this paradigm when trainin=
g future AI systems to perform tasks at or beyond the frontier of human kno=
wledge. In this regime, producing an effective oversight signal carries var=
ious challenges:</p>
<ol><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Oversight may become increasingly nois=
y due to problems being fundamentally difficult, e.g. for problems where ex=
perts disagree on the correct solution (despite agreeing there is an object=
ively correct solution).</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Our oversight=
 signal might have <span style=3D"font-style: italic;"><a href=3D"https://a=
lignment.anthropic.com/2025/recommended-directions/#h.5sp6gxdxd4ww">systema=
tic</a></span><a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/recommended-d=
irections/#h.5sp6gxdxd4ww">&nbsp;</a><span style=3D"font-style: italic;"><a=
 href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/recommended-directions/#h.5sp=
6gxdxd4ww">errors</a></span>, for example stemming from mistakes by human o=
verseers.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Oversight may become increas=
ingly expensive to obtain in sufficient quantity, because it relies on spec=
ialized human labor (e.g. domain experts) or expensive evaluation procedure=
s (e.g. performing experiments). </li></ol>
<p>Scalable oversight refers to the problem of designing oversight mechanis=
ms that scale with the intelligence of the systems we aim to oversee. Ideal=
ly, these mechanisms should allow us to oversee the training of advanced or=
 superhuman AI systems.</p>
<h3 id=3D"h.5sp6gxdxd4ww">Improving oversight despite systematic, exploitab=
le errors in the oversight signal</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">What do we do when our oversight sig=
nal systematically misrepresents the desired task?</span></p>
<p>The most challenging scenarios for scalable oversight occur when our ove=
rsight signal makes systematic errors that our model is smart enough to <a =
href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.12822">learn to exploit</a>. Consider th=
e situation faced by a student taking tests written by a less intelligent t=
eacher: the student might learn to produce answers that <span style=3D"font=
-style: italic;">receive high grades from the teacher</span>&nbsp;even when=
 the student knows the answers are flawed.</p>
<p>More formally, suppose we have access to a proxy reward signal R which m=
akes systematic errors relative to an (inaccessible) ground-truth reward si=
gnal R*. For example, R might reflect answers which fallible human annotato=
rs judge to be correct, while R* reflects actually-correct answers.</p>
<p>In some cases, the difference between R and R* may not matter for traini=
ng purposes. However, if our model is sophisticated enough to accurately mo=
del R - R* (e.g. if the model has a good understanding of human error), the=
n training against R might produce a model which <a href=3D"https://deepmin=
d.google/discover/blog/specification-gaming-the-flip-side-of-ai-ingenuity/"=
>systematically</a>&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.12822">explo=
its</a>&nbsp;errors in R (e.g. by responding to questions with answers whic=
h seem correct to human overseers, but do not actually reflect the model=E2=
=80=99s best guess at a correct answer).</p>
<p>We are interested in techniques which leverage access to M to help us im=
prove our oversight, allowing us to build a new proxy R=E2=80=99 which more=
 closely matches R*.</p>
<p>In order to study this problem, we suggest the creation of testbeds wher=
e, starting with a student model M and a reward signal R*, we:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Intentionally introduce systematic err=
ors into R* to get a training signal R.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;=
">Ensure that M understands the systematic errors made by R. For example, w=
e could do this by providing M a system prompt that explains some of R=E2=
=80=99s errors.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Train M against R, pos=
sibly after applying some scalable oversight technique (e.g. augmenting R w=
ith <a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/recommended-directions/=
#h.fhf8sfxv5kby">debate</a>, or <a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/=
2025/recommended-directions/#h.1sk9rx1vpg0n">only training on episodes</a>&=
nbsp;where we=E2=80=99re very confident R is correct).</li><li style=3D"mar=
gin-left: 36pt;">Evaluate M=E2=80=99s performance against R*.</li></ul>
<h3 id=3D"h.fhf8sfxv5kby">Recursive oversight</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we achieve good oversight by boo=
tstrapping from bad oversight?</span></p>
<p>One approach to scalable oversight is to develop oversight mechanisms th=
at <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2206.05802">incorporate AI assistance</=
a>, and which therefore might scale with AI progress. For example:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Task=
 decomposition</span>&nbsp;(<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.08575">Ch=
ristiano et al., 2018</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2109.10862">Wu =
et al., 2021</a>) aims to break down difficult tasks into subtasks each of =
which can be effectively supervised.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><=
span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Adversarial techniques</span>&nbsp;such as=
 debate (<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/1805.00899">Irving et al., 2018</=
a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.08702">Michael et al., 2023</a>; =
<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.06782">Khan et al., 2024</a>; <a href=
=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.04622">Kenton et al., 2024</a>) and prover-v=
erifier games (<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.13692">Kirchner et al.=
, 2024</a>) pit competing AI systems against each other. The hope is that t=
he only equilibrium in these adversarial games is for the model to perform =
as well as they can.</li></ul>
<p>More formally, these approaches involve starting with an imperfect rewar=
d signal R (e.g. human evaluator approval) and developing a pipeline=E2=80=
=94which may involve consulting AI assistants that were trained using R=E2=
=80=94for creating an improved reward signal R=E2=80=99. Ideally, this proc=
ess can then be repeated to generate further improvements R=E2=80=99=E2=80=
=99, R=E2=80=99=E2=80=99=E2=80=99, etc.</p>
<p>There=E2=80=99s already been substantial work along these lines, and we=
=E2=80=99d be excited to see more.</p>
<h3 id=3D"h.1sk9rx1vpg0n">Weak-to-strong and easy-to-hard generalization</h=
3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we get good performance from bad=
 oversight + generalization?</span></p>
<p>Instead of trying to <a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/rec=
ommended-directions/#h.fhf8sfxv5kby">bootstrap</a>&nbsp;from imperfect rewa=
rd signals to more accurate reward signals, another approach to scalable ov=
ersight involves using an imperfect reward signal as-is while hoping for fa=
vorable generalization properties. We discuss here two such approaches: wea=
k-to-strong generalization and easy-to-hard generalization.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Weak-to-strong generalization</span>&n=
bsp;(<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.09390">Burns et al., 2023</a>; <=
a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.13647">Yang et al., 2024</a>). When st=
udying weak-to-strong generalization, we train strong AI systems using a re=
ward signal generated by a weak overseer and evaluate performance according=
 to a held-out gold-standard oversight signal (e.g. the ground-truth answer=
s where available). For example, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.0939=
0">Burns et al., 2023</a>&nbsp;study the effect of training GPT-4 with over=
sight from GPT-2. Pessimistically, the strong learner (GPT-4 in this exampl=
e) could learn to imitate the mistakes of the weak overseer (GPT-2). But op=
timistically, the strong learner could generalize to perform the task bette=
r than the weak overseer. Notably, there might be <span style=3D"font-style=
: italic;">unsupervised</span>&nbsp;ways to improve weak-to-strong generali=
zation, such as regularizing the learner to be self-consistent (<a href=3D"=
https://arxiv.org/abs/2212.03827">Burns et al., 2022</a>; <a href=3D"https:=
//arxiv.org/abs/2306.09983">Furi et al., 2023</a>).</p>
<p>We are excited about research on improving or measuring weak-to-strong g=
eneralization. For example:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Developing testbeds where we have acce=
ss to oversight signals of varying quality, such as using <a href=3D"https:=
//arxiv.org/abs/2210.10760">models of varying scales</a>&nbsp;as overseers.=
</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Exploring differences in weak-to-stro=
ng generalization between tasks, e.g. study the difference between tasks wh=
ich are represented in training corpora vs. those which are novel to the mo=
del.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Exploring weak-to-strong generali=
zation for process-based supervision, in addition to outcome supervision.</=
li></ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Easy-to-hard generalization</span>&nbs=
p;(<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.18433">Ding et al., 2024</a>; <a h=
ref=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2401.06751">Hase et al., 2024</a>; <a href=3D"=
https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.09472">Sun et al., 2024</a>). Instead of trainin=
g strong AI systems on low-quality labels for the tasks we actually want th=
em to perform, we could instead restrict to training on <span style=3D"font=
-style: italic;">easy</span>&nbsp;tasks for which we can confidently produc=
e high-quality labels. For example, after fine-tuning a large pretrained mo=
del on easy math problems, to what extent does the model generalize to also=
 performing well on difficult math problems? This approach might be especia=
lly useful when we expect our oversight signal on hard tasks to be <a href=
=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/recommended-directions/#h.5sp6gxdx=
d4ww">systematically erroneous</a>, such that the learner is incentivized t=
o imitate our oversight errors.</p>
<p>As above, we are excited about research on measuring or improving easy-t=
o-hard generalization. We are especially interested in topics at the inters=
ection of these two generalization approaches; for example:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">How does supervising with high-quality=
 data on unrepresentative tasks <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.13215=
">trade off against</a>&nbsp;supervising with low-quality data on represent=
ative tasks?</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Are there useful ideas to=
 draw on from the literature on noisy label learning (learning p(y|x) in th=
e presence of unrepresentative data) or noisy domain learning (learning p(x=
) in the presence of unrepresentative data)?</li></ul>
<h3 id=3D"h.5sty9kp0hdic">Honesty</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we identify when our models are =
being honest, even if we can=E2=80=99t judge the accuracy of their response=
s?</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;"></span></p>
<p>The central challenge of scalable oversight in settings with <a href=3D"=
https://alignment.anthropic.com/2025/recommended-directions/#h.5sp6gxdxd4ww=
">systematic, exploitable overseer error</a>&nbsp;is that models might lear=
n to produce answers which appear correct to overseers, even if the model k=
nows the answer to be incorrect. It might seem that the only way to solve t=
his problem is by improving our oversight signal to make fewer errors. Howe=
ver, there is another source of hope: that there might be a common, identif=
iable structure to <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">honest</span>&nbsp;m=
odel responses. That is, we may be able to identify responses that the mode=
l believes to be correct not by comparing them to our own best guess (i.e. =
the oversight signal) but by <a href=3D"https://docs.google.com/document/d/=
1WwsnJQstPq91_Yh-Ch2XRL8H_EpsnjrC1dwZXR37PC8/edit?usp=3Dsharing">leveraging=
 the model=E2=80=99s own knowledge</a>&nbsp;about whether it is responding =
honestly.</p>
<p>There has been substantial prior work on identifying language model repr=
esentations of truth (<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2212.03827">Burns et=
 al., 2022</a>;&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2304.13734">Azaria &a=
mp; Mitchell, 2023</a>; <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.06824">Marks =
&amp; Tegmark, 2023</a>) and using them to classify or control model genera=
tions (<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.01405">Zou et al., 2023</a>;&n=
bsp;<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.06681">Panickssery et al., 2024</=
a>;&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2306.03341">Li et al., 2023</a>;&=
nbsp;<a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.01037">Mallen et al., 2024</a>).=
 We would be interested in work which studies the <a href=3D"https://arxiv.=
org/abs/2312.03729">circumstances under which</a>&nbsp;these techniques are=
 useful, especially with a focus on situations where models have learned to=
 give non-truthful answers.</p>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2 id=3D"h.9kn914d5mpvx">Adversarial robustness</h=
2>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we ensure AI systems behave as d=
esired despite adversarial attacks?</span></p>
<p>Deployed AI systems are placed in adversarial environments, where they s=
ometimes encounter inputs specifically designed to cause undesired behavior=
. For example, users might try to jailbreak AI chatbots, or a sophisticated=
 AI might try to circumvent a <a href=3D"https://alignment.anthropic.com/20=
25/recommended-directions/#h.dos4q2vcvwwj">weaker AI monitor</a>. While the=
re is substantial research on improving the adversarial robustness of AI sy=
stems, we think there are still underexplored areas, especially in:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Better characterizing the attack surfa=
ces future adversaries might use. While adversaries today typically attack =
models via direct prompting, other attack types are possible such as <a hre=
f=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.13722">poisoning pretraining corpora</a>&nb=
sp;or <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.13352">hiding malicious content=
 in websites to hijack AI agents</a>.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">=
Building practical, scalable defenses against misuse&nbsp;of AI systems tha=
t interfere minimally with benign use; see <a href=3D"https://alignment.ant=
hropic.com/2025/recommended-directions/#h.a2hnl4sly5t5">below</a>&nbsp;for =
example.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Developing better measures of=
 the practical reliability of defenses; see <a href=3D"https://alignment.an=
thropic.com/2025/recommended-directions/#h.28jqmoodh6ap">below</a>&nbsp;for=
 more detail.</li></ul>
<h3 id=3D"h.28jqmoodh6ap">Realistic and differential benchmarks for jailbre=
aks</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">How do we measure the real-world har=
m caused by misusing AI systems?</span></p>
<p>Language models are susceptible to jailbreaks: users induce models to re=
spond to questions that they=E2=80=99d otherwise refuse by prompting them i=
n clever ways. However we ultimately don=E2=80=99t care if the model respon=
ds to all questions it would refuse by default; we care if it responds to q=
uestions with useful answers that enable dangerous misuse in practice.</p>
<p>We would thus like benchmarks that capture the <span style=3D"font-style=
: italic;">realistic, differential harm</span>&nbsp;that can result from ad=
versaries jailbreaking and misusing models. For example, <a href=3D"https:/=
/arxiv.org/abs/2402.10260">Souly et al. (2024)</a>&nbsp;and <a href=3D"http=
s://arxiv.org/abs/2410.09024">Andriushchenko et al. (2024)</a>&nbsp;offer a=
 promising start towards assessing real risk by testing whether jailbreaks =
induce models to <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">capably</span>&nbsp;ca=
use harm (rather than just measuring non-refusal). Here are some directions=
 for expanding these kinds of benchmarks: </p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Measuring the <span style=3D"font-styl=
e: italic;"><a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.07918">differential impac=
t </a></span>of an attack, i.e. whether models enable human adversaries to =
accomplish tasks that they couldn=E2=80=99t otherwise. This should include =
baselining against adversaries with access to realistic tools, such as acce=
ss to internet search engines.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Focusin=
g on harmful use-cases that are <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">realist=
ic</span>. An adversary probably doesn=E2=80=99t need a model to cut down a=
 stop sign, but would need a model to aid with a cyberattack on a specific =
piece of software.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Measuring how <span=
 style=3D"font-style: italic;"><a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.15043"=
>universal</a></span>&nbsp;different attacks are, both across inputs and ac=
ross models. First, this is important because a malicious task might requir=
e multiple queries, and it will be harder for an adversary to complete all =
queries if they need a specific jailbreak for each. Similarly, if jailbreak=
s transfer across models, then a closed-weights production model could be a=
ttacked through an API using jailbreaks discovered using a gradient-based a=
ttack on open-weights models. </li></ul>
<p>Beyond the above desiderata, we=E2=80=99d also like benchmarks that capt=
ure how likely real humans are to discover jailbreaks on their own. This is=
 because humans are often able to come up with simple attacks that automate=
d pipelines miss. We would value benchmarks that track what kinds of attack=
s actual humans would find given defenses, using differing amounts of resou=
rces, since this could help surface model weaknesses that aren=E2=80=99t re=
flected in automated jailbreaking attacks. </p>
<h3 id=3D"h.a2hnl4sly5t5">Adaptive defenses</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Can we develop safeguards that adapt=
 to attackers?</span></p>
<p>It=E2=80=99s common to think about defenses against adversaries as a pre=
-deployment problem: we apply interventions to make the model more robust, =
then deploy the model with these interventions. This means defenses are <sp=
an style=3D"font-style: italic;">static</span>, and do not respond to adapt=
ive adversaries. </p>
<p>A less-explored line of research focuses on <span style=3D"font-style: i=
talic;">adaptive</span>&nbsp;defenses that depend on prior model and advers=
ary behavior. Some concrete research directions here include:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Inte=
r-query defenses:</span>&nbsp;An adversary attacking a model will likely tr=
y many prompts before getting the model to generate a harmful output, or re=
quire many harmful outputs in order to complete a malicious task. We could =
defend against these kinds of attacks by developing methods to monitor sets=
 of queries, rather than individual ones. Such methods would need to identi=
fy subsets of suspicious queries from a much larger set of user queries, an=
d be able to infer high-level tasks from low-level subtasks.</li><li style=
=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;"><a href=3D"https:=
//arxiv.org/abs/2411.07494v1">Rapid response</a></span><span style=3D"font-=
weight: 700;">:</span>&nbsp;After an adversary finds an attack, we=E2=80=99=
d like to patch the model as quickly as possible. Can we design adaptive sy=
stems that quickly patch working attacks? And even better, can we patch the=
 system to the point where the adversary gains no useful information from t=
he attack?</li></ul>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2 id=3D"h.y9w2s9297wao">Miscellaneous</h2>
<p>Lastly, we want to highlight two areas that are promising for further re=
search but that don=E2=80=99t fall cleanly into the categories above.</p>
<h3 id=3D"h.fmrwaolmz7sm">Unlearning dangerous information&nbsp;and capabil=
ities</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Given a model that has already learn=
ed something dangerous, can we make the model unlearn it?</span></p>
<p>Large language models learn a large amount of information during pretrai=
ning, including knowledge and capabilities we would rather they not have. T=
his problem has spurred research into <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2409=
.18025">machine unlearning</a>. However, the problem remains largely unsolv=
ed: it remains relatively easy to extract apparently unlearned information =
from models with either whitebox or blackbox&nbsp;access to the model. This=
 problem is increasingly pressing given capabilities improvements in domain=
s like biology and coding that may be useful for <a href=3D"https://arxiv.o=
rg/abs/2403.03218">biological or cyber attacks</a>. </p>
<p>Hence, we encourage research into new methods for unlearning information=
 in LLMs. We suspect that there is ample room for progress, and we encourag=
e research into ambitious forms of unlearning, aimed at producing models wh=
ich behave near-identically to models that were never trained on unlearned =
data (even after <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.08827">further fine-=
tuning to elicit the unlearned knowledge</a>). </p>
<h3 id=3D"h.ws6luqcbcg3p">Learned governance for multi-agent alignment</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">How can we guard against risks that =
emerge from many interacting AI agents?</span></p>
<p>Transformative AI is likely to not be a =E2=80=9Csingle AI=E2=80=9D but =
instead arrive in the form of <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">many</spa=
n>&nbsp;instances of (possibly different) AIs interacting to solve difficul=
t problems. Importantly, <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">even if</span>=
&nbsp;each individual instance is aligned to human values, the resulting mu=
lti-agent system can exhibit a host of novel failure modes that result from=
 poor coordination:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Each instance produces a small negativ=
e externality that the instance dismisses as negligible, but that results i=
n substantial harm in the aggregate.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">A=
 critical problem is noticed by an instance and is reported to another inst=
ance, which reports it to another instance, and so on, without ever being b=
rought to the attention of a human/instance which can resolve the issue.</l=
i><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">A critical problem is noticed by several=
 instances, each of which doesn=E2=80=99t respond due to unclear responsibi=
lity.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Important information required f=
or solving a problem is not shared to the relevant instances because those =
instances did not share information of the problem.</li></ul>
<p>These failure modes are highly familiar from human society, and might si=
milarly be amenable to be alleviated by good <span style=3D"font-style: ita=
lic;">governance</span>. In particular, to avoid multi-agent failure modes =
we might impose restrictions on which actions can be taken in which context=
, or we might incentivize certain =E2=80=9Cprosocial=E2=80=9D behavior. Imp=
ortantly, it might be feasible to <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">learn=
</span>&nbsp;this governance from observations so that it adapts to novel d=
ynamics and failure modes.</p>
<p>This research direction appears ripe for theory-driven approaches levera=
ging insights from game theory as well as empirical investigations.</p>
</d-article><d-appendix style=3D"=E2=80=99background:" hsla(40,20%,30%,0.05=
);=3D"" margin-top:=3D"" 120px;=3D"" padding-top:=3D"" 100px=E2=80=99=3D"" =
id=3D"appendix">



<h3 id=3D"h.w4sexnj6v6d3">Acknowledgements</h3>
<p>We thank Michael Lepori and Atticus Geiger for feedback on a draft.</p>

